<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-204-064  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 204 064.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  March 5 1990 n290 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Rejecting a bid? See you in court. (awards of statetelecommunications contracts is leading to law suits)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Korzeniowski, Paul.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>An increasing number of state telecommunications service contractawards are being contested in court.andP;  Challenges have beenlaunched by unsuccessful bidders in California, Connecticut,Florida, Illinois, Indiana, Maryland, New York and Texas over thepast few years.andP;  Industry analysts cite two main factors for thisphenomenon.andP;  First, in the competitive integrated voice-datamarket, state contracts ranging in value from $4 million to $200million per year are of increasing importance.andP;  Secondly, vendorsspend millions of dollars preparing responses to state governmentrequests for proposals.andP;  As a result, they tend to view theincremental expense of appealing the decision, which may result inbeing awarded a share of the contract, as an extension of theevaluation process.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TelecommunicationsCommunications Service SuppliersIntegrated Voice-DataGovernment ContractsLaw SuitState Government.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>